<font color="#FF0000">MEMORIAL DAY</font><br>
<tt>Tue May 27 16:32:02 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Hey Teach-I also am troubled by those things you stated. Hell, in the five grades my daughter attended, it was never discussed what either Veteran's Day or Memorial Day signify. My daughter has a friend whose uncle died in Vietnam. His name is Bruce Clayton Brogotti. I don't have the names of my fallen comrades and I just wanted to honor one here, that's why I list his name. Anyway, she has a real curiosity and feels a genuine loss of here uncle she never met. I have spent the last month trying to find out all I could for her and how she could honor him that will make her feel that is OK to do so. Previously, she had been stumbling around with this sense of loss that she hasn't been able to set right. She never knew what Memorial Day really meant other than a day off from school. She look foward to this Memorial Day for her and her uncle's sake.<br><br>
Those things that you spoke of that tends to dilute the significance of these two days is why I reacted the way I did. In my own feeble way, I want to try to keep Memorial Day as pure and on focused as I can.<br><br>
Saying that, I am also guilty of that which I criticized. I spent much time not just remembering the deaths of those from my unit, but thinking of Chet, John, Mike, Art, and the many other vets I have had exchanges with on this site, and thanking the fishing gods, that they came home so I had the chance to meet and befriend them. 'nough said.
